	Great for solo travellers	The rooms are just like in the pics on their own site - cabins styled like the early part of the last century. There's a shelf and clothes rail above the bed, draws and luggage space underneath.Views come with the noise of the west side highway, at the back is quieter. My room overlooked a courtyard with trees. AC above the window, and a wall fan.The bathrooms are at the end of each hall, with lockable units for each shower and toilet. I never waited for either. Very nice tiling and rainfall showers.Nice touches: wood panelled rooms, with soft panels around the bed, free replaceable bottled water, old school decor details.The cafe and ballroom closed after the recent licensing controversies. A new cafe is coming soon, looking like a Parisian cafe - may be open by now.About 5% of the rooms on my floor had long term residents in their unrestored rooms. Rooms were a little smelly from the cleaning products used. The beds are right next to the doors, so you hear corridor sounds.Location is excellent - west village, just south of meatpacking, subway a few blocks north at 14th st.Great for $99 in NYC, and a very stylish hotel, in a retro/quirky way.	
Nov 21 2009 	Great location really funky cheapest and best value in NYC I'd say."	I was gutted I had to leave my little nest in The Jane. I WAS prepared for the size of the single cabin room but not prepared for the dinky space saving touches that came with it...I had a huge suitcase and did endless shopping and it never felt cluttered. They get some things really right...bathrobe with pockets for traipsing to the shower, refilled water bottle every day, iPod dock and radio, DVD player and telly, free (working and fast) wifi. And that was stuff I reckon you shouldn't expect for the price so to get it is a real bonus.I am a big boutique hotel fan and love my luxuries - so I came prepared (bring flip flops for the shower!) My biggest worry was the lack of en suite and honestly, I didn't mind a bit in reality. If you're REALLY squeamish then maybe think twice, but I'm quite a princess and there were NO stinks, kinks or sticking plasters in the showers. In 5 days! Again, for the price and for the 'cool factor' I got over myself pretty quickly!My room wasn't noisy, there were no smelly corridors or weirdos that went bump in the night (but I was prepared to tolerate them all if they happened). The bar downstairs is cool and the bar staff mostly really chatty to my lone female traveller self. I peeked into the ballroom (due to open in a few weeks apparently) and was BLOWN AWAY by it's funky, eclectic, dishevelled in a good way decor. it will be a GREAT asset and there's already a cool little cafe on site. Perfect location too - less than 10 minutes to the subway and RIGHT there in Meatpacking/Greenwich/East Village. Honestly, RIGHT there. Amazing.Sure, you could pay double and get an en suite somewhere a bit dull and dreary without an ounce of real cool. You could pay triple and do the real boutique thing and not have to worry about wearing pajamas at night to go to the bathroom. Or you could stay at The Jane, pack an open mind and some flip flops and love every minute of 