Oct 26 2009 	Interesting place	My in-flight magazine had a review of this hotel that made it sound like the hot spot of NYC. It is in a good area, with lots of restaurant options and small shops, and the subway is about 4 blocks away. The rooms are interesting. It is all about conserving energy, which I like, and it was comfortable, but the single bed is quite small and stiff. We did not get our own bathroom, I don't know if that is an option, but the shared bathrooms were clean and rarely busy. My main problem was the smell in the hall way and the noise in the middle of the night. There was a terrible smell all throughout the hallway, it made me gag each and every time I forgot to hold my breath while walking to or out of my room. I never habituated to the smell. However, when I entered my room I couldn't smell it anymore, so it was ok. The noise though, it wasn't constant, but the walls are paper thin and you can hear everything from all of the other rooms. I believe this place is very popular with young men, and on our first night at 4 AM, one of these men decided to kick our door and start screaming. He then said, &quot;oh S***, there is someone in this room, their stuff was all over the bed this afternoon&quot;. I then wondered how he knew my stuff was all over the bed, the only way would be for him to have a key and access to my room while I was out. This was not comfortable at all, but thankfully, I didn't leave anything of value in my room, and nothing was missing after all. You will definitely hear the delightful noises from the hallway as these young people arrive at all times of the night drunk and excited. Overall, the hotel is cute, the room is comfortable enough (definitely not the ritz), but don't expect this to be a place of quiet rest.	
Oct 15 2009 	Perfect for my first experience of NYC great location!	Like other reviewers on here I was a bit concerned about the Jane prior to our trip. We initially booked our stay back in June and loved the idea of this place, it's quirkiness and also the fact it was a budget hotel. The location of it was also instrumental in our choice as I really wanted to be in West Village having read about it's 'vibe'. So we booked up and were happy. You don't even need to pay a downpayment when you book so if for any reason you have to cancel your trip you don't get charged.Fast forward a few months and just before we leave I read on here a few horror stories about noise from the newly opened bar, roaches and bedbugs and I have to admit in doubting my decision. So I arrived with a can of RAID in my suitcase prepared for all eventualities... But, I have to say hand on heart, the hotel was excellent. Not a bug or roach in sight. The rooms and bathrooms were spotless and cleaned regularly. Rooms cleaned and bed linen changed/turned down daily whilst there. The staff were friendly and accommodating, from the doormen to the lift operator. Everyone was really helpful. And we heard no noise at all (though I suppose we were on the fifth floor). Considering how old the building is, and how small the rooms are, they are very well insulated as you cannot hear much going on once inside your own room. There was even work going on above us and on our floor (they are still refurbishing parts of the hotel) and we never heard a thing. We were put in 2 adjoining rooms on the 5th floor. The tiny cabin like rooms are cleverly designed like ships cabins with a full mirror on one wall so you don't feel too claustraphobic as it creates the feeling of it being bigger. Your suitcase goes under the bed. There is a digital safe in the drawer under the bed also (2 large drawers in all). There are railings on each wall to hang stuff up. There is an iPod dock/alarm clock, a widescreen TV, air con and a wall fan, a robe, x3 towels and a complimentary bottle of water included in the price also. The rooms are powered by an electrical 'key' which you plug in when you enter the room. Bear in mind that you take it out when youleave so anything you leave charging (ie phone) won't be charged as the electricity is only on when this thing is plugged in. Its a good idea to conserve power. Very green!We were early-ish risers due to wanting to explore in our 5 day trip so we got up about 7.30 each day. The bathrooms are situated at either ends of each floor and had two showers (with doors you lock) and two toilets in both. The showers were wonderful, water always hot and shower gel, shampoo and conditioners are also included in their wall dispensers inside the shower. By the bathroom sinks there are hairdryers. I can honestly say in our whole time there we never had to queue to have a shower or if one was occupied you just wandered to the other side to use that one instead. Our floor had quite a few residents (you can tell from their doors as they have key locks instead of the electrical system the hotel uses) but all of them we met were pleasant and friendly, esp one little guy that I kept meeting in the bathrooms while he brushed his teeth. He was very nice but I never found out his name (5th floor opp room 519). Admittedly there is a kind of musty smell in some corridors mostly because some of the residents may smoke in their rooms but on the whole it wasn't unpleasant and there are air fresheners on the walls too. Our room windows faced inward so you only overlook another room's window opposite but there are slatted blinds provided for your privacy at night.The only gripe we had was that the bar in the hotel was closed to residents practically every night we stayed for &quot;a Private Party&quot;. There is a small pub like bar and a larger ballroom bar next door and these were off limits to guests when it was hired out and it was guest list only We were told that whilst the bar is IN the Jane Hotel, its privately owned and rented out regularly to whomever and the hotel has not much say in the matter. But the Jane is in a great area for plenty of other pubs/bars/resturants anyway all within a short stroll so it wasn't a problem. Plus the one night we DID get in the bar, the drinks were $12 dollars each!! And that was for a meagre glass of wine. So my advice go somewhere else for a tipple as IMO the owner of the Jane Bar must be a bit pretentious to charge those prices in a budget hotel. There is a Cafe/Coffee shop opening soon in the lobby area which looks to be good so that be a alternative to the bar. In the meantime the nearest deli Nonno Gourmet does loads of hot food, bagels, coffee to take out and if you walk North towards 14th St and 9th Av in the Meatpacking area there is a really cool diner that does fabulous breakfasts!The area itself is great and if you are relatively fit, you can easily walk southwards towards Downtown/Wall Street via Washington St or North towards Midtown (or get on subway at 14th St) We walked everywhere and the West Village is my favourite part of New York. Hudson St, Bleeker St are all close by and have a great choice of food places to eat.Oh and one last thing, if you are new to New York like me and didn't realise prices didn't include taxes, the Jane's $99 per night DOES NOT include taxes. Its not shown on your confirmation invoice either so don't get caught out. All in all plus taxes its approx $117 dollars per night.If I was to go back again, I would happily stay there again, with friends or on my own. I recommend New York (fell in love with the place) and I recommend the Jane experience. It's not the Hilton or anything posh but its quirky and unusual and definately a talking point but in a good way... Thanks for a pleasant stay and I hope to be back!	
Oct 14 2009 	Perfect for what I wanted.	I stayed at the Jane for 4 nights in September and loved it. The tiny room was indeed tiny but as a first timer in NY this wasn't a problem, I was traveling alone and only looking for a place to sleep/wash/relax. The shared bathroom was clean my entire trip, not a single bed bug (I checked), the staff were really helpful and friendly, the other guests an eccentric mix of people like me and the long term residents who are still in situ. Some people have complained about the location, it's not easily accessible by subway but it took me a mere 20 minutes to walk to 5th Avenue and NY taxis are cheap for night time travel. At $99 a night +tax for Manhattan I really couldn't complain but this is not a hotel for people accustomed to luxury or Hilton type hotels. It's quirky in the best possible way and I'll be back.	
