Oct 5 2009 	Great Value for a Short-Term Stay	The Jane provides excellent value for the price. I stayed for a week on business, and would likely recommend this hotel to budget travelers. High points: Charming historic building, an old elevator run by an operator, clean bathrooms. The small rooms are smartly designed, with shelves, overhead storage, drawers under the bed, hooks on the door, and several sliding hooks on each side of the room from which to hang clothing or towels. High speed internet was reliable and fast. My room was well-cleaned upon arrival.Things to be aware of: *The bathrooms, while clean, are truly shared. In other words, it is not one stand-alone bathroom that you enter and have to yourself, as it is in some hotels with shared bathrooms. The bathroom on my floor had two sinks, two shower stalls (with full-length doors) and two toilet stalls (with full length doors as well). If you are not comfortable using the toilets, sinks/mirrors, or entering/exiting the shower with others in the room - including those of the opposite sex - this may be an issue for you.*The hotel provides a set of disposable flip-flops, but mine both broke on my very first trip to the bathroom. You may wish to bring footwear of your own.*Shampoo, shower gel, and conditioner are provided in the showers from pumps. Bath towels and hand towels were provided, but not washcloths. You may wish to bring your own washcloth and/or shower poof.*Tissues were not provided in the rooms or the bathrooms. *The permanent residents of the building - mostly older, downtrodden types - may seem intimidating at first but I never encountered a problem.* The rooms are truly small. They are actually smaller than they look in the photos, so be prepared. * It's a bit of a walk to the subway station (about 6 minutes) and cabs don't pass the hotel as frequently as on other streets, so you may find yourself walking over to the next block to hail one. This, combined with the flight of stairs you need to ascend to enter the front door, makes this hotel less suitable for people with limited mobility or with large amounts of luggage. I sense that the management, possibly in part because of the location, wants to make the place a hip, trendy, boutique hotel of sorts. I hope this doesn't distract them from continuing to strive for what most travelers are really looking for: clean, safe, well-appointed rooms that are also affordable. Another reviewer's comment about the &quot;hipper-than-thou&quot; young desk clerk also suggest the hotel's inclination toward the trendy ambiance. But really, how hip can you be wearing a bellboy's hat?	
