Jul 28 2009 	Great for travelers who need a nice safe place to sleep and that's it	I came to NYC for 4 days to see my girlfriend, so I wasn't going to be spending much time in my room. I've always been opposed to the idea of spending a trip in a big expensive hotel room watching TV, so I looked around and found the Jane. Rather than other dorm-style hostels, I wanted a private room with a BED TO SLEEP IN DURING THE NIGHT AND THAT WAS IT. And that is exactly what the charming Jane Hotel provided.My room was small (only 50 square feet) but was by NO MEANS CRAMPED FOR ONE PERSON...cozy would best describe it. I would call it a hotel bedroom rather than a hotel room. The room was VERY CLEAN and surprisingly well furnished, however. Complete with AC, fan, telephone, flatscreen TV with cable, clean linens/towels, drawers, and a safe, I was very surprised upon entering the room. The pictures from the website do not lie in what the rooms look like. Down the hall was the very clean and easily accessible COMMUNAL BATHROOMS with showers. The 1908 building originally held sailors and some Titanic survivors, and still had that old-style charm. There was a nice bar and lounge area that always had some big party with live bands going on every night. I stayed during the last stages of the Jane's construction (they're adding bigger rooms on some floors and a restaurant off the lobby that are scheduled to be completed by Fall 2009)The staff was VERY VERY FRIENDLY, always offering assistance when needed and greeting you with very friendly attitudes. They made me feel like I lived there, which was something I've never felt from the cold, cookie-cutter service of big-name hotels. The Jane is in a GREAT LOCATION between the Meatpacking District and the West Village, really close to great restaurants, shopping, and transit stops. For my first time on my own in NYC, I couldn't have picked a better area to start off in.NOTE TO TRAVELERS: The Jane hotel does have permanent tenants who live i